<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Document: a document in the handwriting of the author ]">AD</abbr>, <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 2, 1772-93, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger B</span>, 121.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Virginia Gazette</span> (Purdie and Dixon; Williamsburg) reported on 4 Aug. that a Sum of Money, amounting nearly to 1000 l. is to be raised by Subscription from the several Counties, and paid into the Hands of the Treasurer, to defray the Expenses of those Gentlemen at the Congress. An account book among the treasurers records at <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span> indicates that most of the counties paid 15, the amount each was called on to contribute (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ David John Mays. &lt;i&gt;Edmund Pendleton, 17211803: A Biography&lt;/i&gt;. 2 vols. Cambridge, Mass., 1952. ]">Mays, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Pendleton</span></span>, 1:277).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0002">2</a>
 
   <p>All money from here to the end of the month is in Pennsylvania currency. GWs <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Pocket-day-Book or Cash-Memorandums, 9 Aug. 177227 May 1773, 29 May 177322 March 1774, 26 Oct. 17743 May 1775. Manuscript in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. 24 March-31 October 1774. Manuscript in Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, Calif. ]">Cash Memoranda, 1772-75</span> lists these travel expenses, including stops at Marlboro, Queen Annes, Annapolis, Rock Hall, Chester, Newcastle, and Wilmington. See also <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-03-02-0004-0015#GEWN-01-03-02-pb-0272" class="document">3:272</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The shoes and boots were for GWs body servant Will (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Pocket-day-Book or Cash-Memorandums, 9 Aug. 177227 May 1773, 29 May 177322 March 1774, 26 Oct. 17743 May 1775. Manuscript in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. 24 March-31 October 1774. Manuscript in Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, Calif. ]">Cash Memoranda, 1772-75</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The money for these items seems to be broken down into several entries in the <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Pocket-day-Book or Cash-Memorandums, 9 Aug. 177227 May 1773, 29 May 177322 March 1774, 26 Oct. 17743 May 1775. Manuscript in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. 24 March-31 October 1774. Manuscript in Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, Calif. ]">Cash Memoranda, 1772-75</span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Philip Marchington, a native of England, settled in Philadelphia in 1771 as a merchant. Marchington, a Tory, left for New York when the British army retired from Philadelphia in 1778. He died in 1808 in Nova Scotia.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0102-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Pocket-day-Book or Cash-Memorandums, 9 Aug. 177227 May 1773, 29 May 177322 March 1774, 26 Oct. 17743 May 1775. Manuscript in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. 24 March-31 October 1774. Manuscript in Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, Calif. ]">Cash Memoranda, 1772-75</span> lists a number of expenses in Philadelphia not found in GWs cash accounts, including expenses for visits to the New Prison, the waxworks, and Provence Island. In his <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Pocket-day-Book or Cash-Memorandums, 9 Aug. 177227 May 1773, 29 May 177322 March 1774, 26 Oct. 17743 May 1775. Manuscript in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. 24 March-31 October 1774. Manuscript in Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, Calif. ]">Cash Memoranda, 1772-75</span>, GW also lists his purchases of Mr [John] Dickinsons Pampt on 8 Sept. and the Bishop of St Asaphs Speach<span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from ',' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2013-07-22]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"> [<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">A Speech, Intended to have been Spoken on the Bill for altering the Charters of the Colony of Massachusetts-Bay. Written by the Rev. Dr. Jonathan Shipley, Lord Bishop of St. Asaph</span>.],</span> and Lord Cambdens Considns on 10 September. Under the date of 23 Sept. GW records a Memm left with Mr Ross the upholder [upholsterer] 5 half Joes to buy furniture with &amp; to be accounted for and on 25 Sept. Memm recd an order from Mr Jno. D: Wilper on Cuthbt Bullett for 25 to be recd for his use.</p>

</div>
</div>
